    <text id="R137715084T">
        <front id="d2">
            <div1 type="summary" id="d3">
                <p>Union General Darius Couch, commanding at Chambersburg, writes to General William
                    Averell, facing advancing Confederate forces in July, 1864. Couch notifies
                    Averell that his train has passed through town, mentions an operator who left
                    his post, and the arrival in town of a man without orders demanding an engine
                    for Averell.</p>
            </div1>
        </front>
        <body id="d4">
            <div1 type="letter" id="d5">
                <head>
                    <name type="recipient">Brig.-Gen. AVERELL:</name>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        <date value="1864-07-29">July 29, 1864.</date>
                        <name type="place">CHAMBERSBURG,</name>
                    </dateline>
                    <salute/>
                </opener>
                <p>At 12.10 p. m. this day operator at Hagerstown left his instrument stating that
                    he had been ordered by you to do so. After 2 p. m. it was reported that a man
                    came to Greencastle, without any orders from Gen. Averell, demanding an engine.
                    You train has just passed through. What is the state of affairs in your front?</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute/>
                    <signed>D. N. COUCH,<lb/> Maj.-Gen.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div1>
        </body>
    </text>
